faq:
  - q: "What does STAR stand for in interviews?"
    a: "STAR stands for Situation, Task, Action, Result. It is the standard framework for answering behavioral interview questions. Situation: the context and constraint. Task: what you specifically needed to accomplish. Action: what you decided and did — this should be 60% of your answer. Result: the quantified outcome. At senior levels, strong STAR answers add a fifth element: Consequence — what happened downstream for the team, product, or business as a result."
  - q: "How long should a STAR interview answer be?"
    a: "90 to 120 seconds for most behavioral questions. Long enough to be substantive, short enough to hold attention. The most common mistake is spending too long on Situation and Task — which should take no more than 20–30 seconds combined. The Action phase should consume most of the time. If your answer runs past 2 minutes, you are over-explaining the context and under-explaining your reasoning."
  - q: "What is a good example of a STAR interview answer?"
    a: "Situation: Our largest enterprise client was threatening to churn over a feature gap in our reporting module. Task: I needed to deliver a solution within 4 weeks or risk losing a $1.8M ARR account. Action: I assessed the gap, found we could build 80% of what they needed in 3 weeks with 2 engineers if we descoped the configurability. I proposed that tradeoff to the client directly, got alignment on what they actually needed vs. what they had originally requested, and led the sprint execution. Result: We shipped the core feature in 19 days. The client renewed for 2 years and expanded the contract by $400K. The descoped configurability shipped 8 weeks later with zero friction because we had set expectations upfront."
  - q: "How do I make STAR answers sound natural — not scripted?"
    a: "STAR answers sound scripted when they are memorized verbatim and recited robotically. To sound natural: practice speaking the story, not reading it. Vary your pacing — slow down on the decision moment. Use first-person singular ('I decided,' 'I made the call') not passive voice ('it was decided'). Pause naturally after the Result. If the interviewer asks a follow-up, engage with it conversationally rather than returning to your script."
  - q: "What is the difference between a mid-level and senior STAR answer?"
    a: "Mid-level STAR answers describe what happened. Senior STAR answers describe what you decided and why — including the alternatives you considered and rejected. The key differences: (1) The Action phase names a specific decision and explains the reasoning behind it. (2) The Result is quantified and connects to a business metric, not just task completion. (3) A Consequence is included — what happened downstream for the team or organization as a result of the outcome."
  - q: "Can I use the same STAR story for multiple questions?"
    a: "Avoid it if possible — interviewers notice, and it signals a thin story bank. If you must reuse a story, reframe it to answer a different dimension: the same project can be the basis for a leadership story, an execution story, or a failure story if you pull out different aspects. But prepare 6–8 distinct stories specifically so you have coverage across all common question categories without repetition."
howto:
  name: "How to Use the STAR Method in Interviews"
  steps:
    - name: "Identify the question category before answering"
      text: "Every behavioral question falls into a category: leadership, conflict, failure, execution, problem-solving, or motivation. Before answering, identify the category — this determines which of your prepared stories to use and which aspect of STAR to emphasize. Leadership questions want more Action. Failure questions want more honest Result and Consequence."
    - name: "Open with Situation in one sentence"
      text: "Set the context without over-explaining. Name the company, the role, the year if relevant, and the core constraint or challenge. Do not tell the backstory of how you got there — start at the moment the challenge began. Target: 10–15 seconds for Situation."
    - name: "Name the Task with stakes"
      text: "What did you specifically need to accomplish, and why did it matter? The stakes elevate the story. 'I needed to ship the feature' is flat. 'I needed to ship within 4 weeks or lose a $1.8M contract' has stakes. Target: 10–15 seconds for Task."
    - name: "Lead the Action with your decision"
      text: "This is where most answers fail. Do not describe a sequence of events — describe a decision. 'I assessed X, concluded Y, and made the call to Z because...' Name the specific choice, the reasoning behind it, and the alternatives you rejected. This is the phase where interviewers decide whether you are senior. Target: 60–70 seconds for Action."
    - name: "Quantify the Result"
      text: "What changed as a measurable outcome? Revenue, retention, latency, cost, team performance. If exact numbers are unavailable, approximate honestly: 'roughly $400K,' '~30% improvement,' 'within 3 weeks.' No numbers = no credibility. Target: 10–15 seconds for Result."
    - name: "Add Consequence for senior roles"
      text: "What happened downstream as a result of your outcome? This is the signal that separates senior from mid-level thinking. The feature shipped — and then what? The team structure changed. The precedent was set. The customer expanded. Adding this layer shows that you think about second-order effects, not just task completion."
